INSERT INTO `wp_options` (`option_id`, `option_name`, `option_value`, `autoload`) VALUES(2615, '_transient_rss_0e98340d518ceed28b29f102e202ba76', 'O:9:"MagpieRSS":19:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:10:{i:0;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:45:"PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/Z-fQJCu618A/";s:8:"comments";s:74:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 30 Nov 2011 22:04:10 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:34:"WebdevelopmentFrameworksPHPRouting";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=718";s:11:"description";s:378:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on...</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3327:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. That&#8217;s why I&#8217;ve decided to start programming a Routing class that mimics Rails routing functionality.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve released this PHP Routing class on Github <a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">here</a>, so you can follow and contribute to it&#8217;s development progress.</p>\n<h4>What does this PHP Routing class do?</h4>\n<p>In short, this class helps you route URL&#8217;s to their corresponding Controller and action methods. You can use different HTTP methods to fully benefit from using REST / resourceful routes. Also, setting up dynamic URL&#8217;s that pass parameters to their corresponding action are no problem.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>REST Routing</li>\n<li>Use different HTTP methods for same URL&#8217;s</li>\n<li>Dynamic URL segments</li>\n<li>Reversed routing, create URL from route</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The class is fairly simple and lightweight, it won&#8217;t do any unnecessary processing. Have a look at the following snippet taken from the example file to get a better understanding on how to use this class in your projects.</p>\n<pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\nrequire ''Router.php'';\n\n$r = new Router();\n\n// maps / to controller ''users'' and method ''index''.\n$r-&gt;match(''/'',''users#index'');\n\n// maps /user/5 to controller ''users'', method ''show'' with parameter ''id'' =&gt; 5\n$r-&gt;match(''/user/:id'',''users#show'');\n\n// maps POST request to /users/ to controller ''users'' and method ''create''\n$r-&gt;match(''/users'',''users#create'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''post''));\n\n// maps GET /users/5/edit to controller ''users'', method ''edit'' with parameters ''id'' =&gt; 5 and saves route as a named route.\n$r-&gt;match(''/users/:id/edit'',''users#edit'',array(''via'' =&gt; ''get'', ''as'' =&gt; ''user_edit_page''));\n\n// echoes /users/5/edit\necho $r-&gt;reverse(''user_edit_page'',array(''id'' =&gt; ''5''));\n\n// maps multiple routes\n// GET /users will map to users#index\n// GET /users/5 will map to users#show\n$r-&gt;resources(''users'',array(''only'' =&gt; ''index,show''));\n\nif($r-&gt;hasRoute()) {\n    // extract controller, action and parameters.\n    extract($r-&gt;getRoute());\n\n    ?&gt;\n    &lt;h1&gt;Route found!&lt;/h1&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Controller: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $controller; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Action: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php echo $action; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Params: &lt;/b&gt;&lt;?php var_dump($params); ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n    &lt;?php\n\n} else {\n    ?&gt;&lt;h1&gt;No route found.&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;?php\n}\n\n?&gt;\n</pre>\n<p>If you&#8217;re using this class and experience any issues, please post them using GitHub&#8217;s issue tracker. Also, feel free to geek around and fork the project to improve this class. </p>\n<p><a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">Watch PHP Routing Class on Github!</a></p>\n<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/Z-fQJCu618A" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:70:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:65:"http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/";}s:7:"summary";s:378:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on...</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/718/php-routing-class-with-rest-routes/">PHP Routing Class which supports REST routing</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3327:"<p>In the last few months I&#8217;ve been looking into all the different PHP frameworks and how they glue things together. One of the most important things in every framework is the way it handles routes. I&#8217;ve been developing Ruby on Rails applications extensively last year and I really like the way Rails handles it&#8217;s routes. That&#8217;s why I&#8217;ve decided to start programming a Routing class that mimics Rails routing functionality.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve released this PHP Routing class on Github <a href="https://github.com/dannyvankooten/PHP-Router">here</a>, so you can follow and contribute to it&#8217;s development progress.</p>\n<h4>What does this PHP Routing class do?</h4>\n<p>In short, thi